issue.title: Attempt to fix duplicate flag issue
issue.body:
Summary:
X-link: https://github.com/facebook/fbthrift/pull/579

CacheLib noticed OSS build failures due to JSONProtocolCommon.cpp being linked into the build twice, after we added a GFLAG to that file.

This diff attempts to fix the issue by depending on thriftprotocol rather than duplicating the files.

The code claims that it couldn't depend on thriftprotocol due to a circular dependency (added in [D24720566](https://www.internalfb.com/diff/D24720566)), but Sandcastle and GitHub Actions is passing, so it doesn't seem to still be an issue.

Differential Revision: D50505357

Refactor processFirstResponse to return ResponseRpcError instead of RocketException

The change is to only have `processFirstResponse` do the step 1, and but leave the step 2) to the callsites, which are only local to the `RocketThriftRequest.cpp`

fbshipit-source-id: e3f1b27a6a537a254d39de573ed44a0f4c77e9f9

Add support for Enum Classes

Summary:
Exhaustivity checking in Hack misses many cases (see [this post](https://fb.workplace.com/groups/hackforhiphop/permalink/24988113060810640/) or D47890092). This diff continues the implementation of a new strict switch gated behind an annotation.

It does so by adding support for enum classes. `HH\MemberOf<name, interface>` is localized as `Tnewtype("HH\MemberOf", [enum; interface])` which is translated into the `EnumClass { name; interface; class_decl }` constructor. However, only class constants which are a subtype of `interface` are included in the `Enum info : Value.t` constructed from it.

As result, not only can a programmer _miss_ constants of an `Enum info`, they can include unnecessary ones too. For these extra labels/members, we add a `Enum_class_label_member_mismatch` errors.

The code relies on type simplification to simplify `HH\MemberOf<name, i1> | HH\MemberOf<name, i2>` to `HH\MemberOf<name (i1 | i2)>`.

Reviewed By: dlreeves

Differential Revision: D49866519

fbshipit-source-id: 92623262cbd87e6f040f4f2f3ba869c8716c7253

Add support for dynamic type

Summary:
Exhaustivity checking in Hack misses many cases (see [this post](https://fb.workplace.com/groups/hackforhiphop/permalink/24988113060810640/) or D47890092). This diff continues the implementation of a new strict switch gated behind an annotation.

It does so by adding support for `dynamic` types. This is done in a way that `dynamic | T` i.e. `~T` is always treated as `T`, except for when `T = noreturn` (i.e. just `dynamic`). In the latter case, a default is required and all other cases are rejected.

fbshipit-source-id: 96c3e051122237d45cb7daf12005bb07697243c9

Store whether a unit is soft deployed in repo mode

Summary:
In repo mode, a unit's **package accessibility** can be one of three options:
- Hard deployed: included in the current deployment, accessible
- Soft deployed: included in the current deployment, warns when accessed
- Not deployed: not included in current deployment, raises undefined

Note that in the first case, we don't need to check package deployment,  and in the third case in repo mode, we'll throw an undefined error on loading of the symbol (and thus, won't check the package violation at all). Therefore, in repo mode, the only case that requires us to check a unit's package is if the unit is soft deployed.

This check is currently very slow to check when we cannot statically deduce a symbol's caller (i.e. in dynamic callsites). So to optimize this, in repo mode, we store a single boolean in the unit that is true if and only if the unit is soft deployed. We can then check that boolean in the dynamic case.

Implementation notes:
- I'd love to add a single bitfield instead of a full boolean to each unit, but it's undefined behavior in C++ to get the offset of a bitfield, and we need to be able to get the offset to access it without doing a callq. If there's another way to do this (that doesn't involve, say, hackily calculating the offset of the bitfield with some garbage like `reinterpret_cast<std::size_t>(&nullPtr->m_softDeployedRepoOnly)`), let me know.

- The field is named as m_softDeployedRepoOnly to make sure it is only accessed in repoAuthoritative mode, and its getter asserts that we're in repo mode only. However, the offset of m_softDeployedRepoOnly is a static constexpr, so I don't really have a way of asserting that the offset is only accessed in repo mode. Would appreciate feedback.

Reviewed By: oulgen

fbshipit-source-id: f82347c1da3513ea584447fccbc06d716e8f375e

add "convert to 'var_dump'" quickfix

Summary:
Change: add a new quickfix for converting `=$x + 1` to valid Hack: `var_dump($x + 1)`

Mitigates  T164253172 when T165204669 is fixed

## Why

- statements with leading `=` like `=$x + 1;` are only allowed in the debugger.
- When users paste from the debugger to Code@FB or Bento notebooks, they get syntax errors
- This change reduces the pain of `=$x + 1` not being allowed

## Perf note

This change introduces some repeat work in parsing but *only* in the case where we have an error about an unexpected `=`, which I doubt is common.

## Advice Welcome

See leading_equals_expr_1.php: we offer a quickfix for changing `foo(=$x)` to `foo(var_dump($x))` and I have a weak preference for not doing so. I think the quickfix is unlikely to be what users want when `=` starts an expression.

Is there a way to not provide the refactoring for cases like `foo(=$x)` without threading extra information through a lot of function calls in the expression parser (`is_top_of_statement` or some such)?

## Follow-on work

**doesn't actually show up in IDE**

There was an off-by-one in our calculation (in our language server) of which quickfixes to show to the user. Fixed in {D49772308}

**no quickfixes at all show up in notebooks**

T165204669

**Too many flavors of Hack syntax**

We currently have at least three flavors of Hack syntax:
- actual Hack: no syntax errors in IDE nor HHVM
- debugger: unspecified
- notebooks (see hh_rewrite_declarations for part of the definition): unspecified

Ideally we will conform and specify where feasible to increase maintainability and learnability-for-aend-users. Looking into it.

See https://www.internalfb.com/diff/D49687153?dst_version_fbid=1768488200255193&transaction_fbid=6924815540915718 for why we seriously consider allowing leading `=` in notebooks

Reviewed By: patriciamckenzie

Differential Revision: D49687153
